  <static seed="777" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/QuadraticEquations/solveQuad330.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>{x\mathopen{}\left(4x+49\right)}={-90}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="20" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{\frac{-9}{4},-10\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>There are a few ways to solve quadratic equations- the easiest way to solve this particular 
type of problem is to use the <em>zero product principle</em>.</p>
<p><m>\begin{aligned}
                     {x\mathopen{}\left(4x+49\right)}={-90}               \amp \Rightarrow {4x^{2}+49x+90}=0 \\
                                    \amp \Rightarrow {\left(4x+9\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+10\right)}=0 \\
                                    \amp  \Rightarrow {\left\{\frac{-9}{4},-10\right\}}
       \end{aligned}</m></p>
<p>This quadratic equation has two distinct, real solutions.</p>
<p>The solutions can be checked by substituting them into the original equation- this is left as an exercise.</p>
</solution>
